# AAA Testing Pattern

All unit tests must follow the Arrange-Act-Assert structure with explicit comments marking each section.

## Structure

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - No clear structure
it('should calculate sum', () => {
  const a = 5;
  const b = 10;
  const result = add(a, b);
  expect(result).toBe(15);
});

// ✅ GOOD - Clear AAA sections
test('should calculate sum', () => {
  // Arrange
  const a = 5;
  const b = 10;

  // Act
  const result = add(a, b);

  // Assert
  expect(result).toBe(15);
});
```

## Section Guidelines

### Arrange
- Set up test data and dependencies
- Create mocks, stubs, or spies
- Configure initial state
- Keep minimal - only what's needed for this test

### Act
- Single action that triggers the behavior being tested
- Should be one line when possible
- Clear separation from Arrange

### Assert
- One or more assertions verifying the outcome
- Test one concept per test
- Use descriptive assertion messages when framework supports it

## Multiple Assertions

When multiple related assertions are needed, keep them in the Assert section:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
test('should create user with defaults', () => {
  // Arrange
  const email = 'test@example.com';

  // Act
  const user = createUser(email);

  // Assert
  expect(user.email).toBe(email);
  expect(user.isActive).toBe(true);
  expect(user.createdAt).toBeInstanceOf(Date);
});
```

## Async Tests

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
test('should fetch data', async () => {
  // Arrange
  const fetcher = mockApi();
  fetcher.mockResolvedValue({ data: 'value' });

  // Act
  const result = await fetchData(fetcher);

  // Assert
  expect(result).toEqual({ data: 'value' });
  expect(fetcher).toHaveBeenCalledWith('/api/data');
});
```

## Param-only “pure” tests

When there is no heavier setup (no mocks, no DOM), you still use **all three section labels**. Bind inputs under **Arrange**—including literals you would otherwise inline into the call—then a single invocation under **Act**:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - parameters are Arrange
test('should return true for valid email', () => {
  // Arrange
  const email = 'user@example.com';

  // Act
  const result = isValidEmail(email);

  // Assert
  expect(result).toBe(true);
});
```

Default for this repo: **always** include `// Arrange`, `// Act`, and `// Assert` so structure stays consistent. Omit a section label only in exceptional cases (agreed with reviewers), not for “short” tests.
